lenders.name: Bennie
lenders.loan_because: My name is Bennie Marie Frazier.  I'm a past Bay Area Nordstrom Wardrobe and Sales Consultant.  After a turbulent divorce , I moved to Abilene, Texas with my son and daughter in 1995 to be near my sister and extended family.  At this time, I was engaged to the love of my life.  However, that was short-livd.  My Finance' became very ill with a heart condition and died 11 months before our wedding.  Although I was emotionally devasted and grief-stricken, I was determined to pursue my dream and opened my shop, "Bennie's Attic" June 2006 in a small town called Sweetwater, Texas, (population 8.000, 40 miles west of Abilene, Texas, population 120,000).  I specialize in High End Designer Women and Children Clothes, Antiques, Art and Collectibles.  My other speciality is High Fashion "Retro" clothes and accessories.  I love the field of fashion and I have 25 plus years of fashion and sales experience.  I also owned and operated 2 clothing boutiques back in the Bay Area.  A popular TV show out of Dallas, Texas by the name "The Texas Country Reporter" discovered my shop in July 2010.  One of the TV show producers walked into my shop unexpectedly and became fascinated by some art from my private collection done by a deceased award winning commercial advertising artist. He asked if  I would be willing to let him do a feature story for TV.  I was very flattered and of course I said yes! He did a fabulous video on my shop and it aired the first time on April 17, 2010.  They've done several reruns already!  Prior to the show being aired on TV, anything that could have gone wrong happened.  My boyfriend lost his job of 5 years and I was forced to sign my house back over to the owner on June 2, 2010 due to a lack of mone to pay my property taxes.  Although the appraisal office agreed to allow me to pay it out in installment payments, the owner would'nt agree to it.  Unfortunately, I'm currently renting my former house.  Although I've lost my home, I don't want to lose my business due to a lack of money to move to Abilene, Texas and expand my business.  My business does well overall.  I'm on a very tight budget.  I'm convinced without a doubt that my sales would increase dramatically if I were to move my business from my current location, Sweetwater, Texas to Abilene, Texas.  I need a larger more modern building with ample parking.  I believe that I have two major edges on my competitors.  I realize that in this economy, consumers want affordable quality fashion and they want and deserve excellent customer service!  I was fortunate to work for the company, Nordstrom, noted for being number one in providing customer service!  I go the extra mile to recruit, please and keep my customers. I'm involved in several community service agencies.  I donate "Back to School" clothes for needy familes.  I also donate what I call "Dress for Success" apparel for women who are entering the workforce but lack the money to purchase an interview outfit or need wardrobe assistance.  I need expansion money badly.  I've located the perfect building.  The Landlord viewed the TV video that the Texas Country Reporter did on my shop and has agreed to give me 6 months free rent, because he says he believes in me and my business ideas.  However, I will be required to pay the monthly "tenant occupancy charge", $950.00, along with my monthly utilities. Whereas, I'm currently paying $375.00 a month shop rent plus utilities.  I need the loan for relocating, setting up a web site, purchasing "point of sale" systems, a surveillance system, advertising, a more efficient business computer system including a lap-top, shop liability insurance, a new shop sign and repay 2 personal loans.  Gosh, I would be estatic if I could get some funds in time for the holidays.  I realize it's a lot of work, but I can do it with your help financially!  One of my business goals in the future is to hire a part-time employee to help with the enormous amount of work that goes into operating a business.  Right now, I work as a part-time mental health crisis worker at night to help offset business expenses.  My boyfriend volunteers an average of 25- 30 hours per week to help me out.  I don't know what I'd do if it were'nt for his help.  I would be happy to send you a copy of the Texas Country Reporter TV video of my shop in the event you wish to view it.  Thank You.  You may call or email me.  (325) 236-3909   Greigfraz4gus@aol.com

lenders.occupational_info:
Acuity Brands’ Sensor Switch, the leading authority on light control solutions in the lighting industry, offers a breakthrough in occupancy sensors – Dual Technology. Sensor Switch offers a series of high-quality occupancy sensors that feature the new dual technology design. It utilizes both Passive Infrared and Microphonics to ensure high accuracy and unbeatable performance. 
Occupancy sensors powered by Sensor Switch’s dual technology can ‘see’ and ‘hear’ occupants to deliver significant energy-savings and end-user convenience. With Passive Infrared or PIR, these occupancy sensors can ‘see’ people by detecting infrared radiated by objects and occupants. Microphonics on the other hand can detect occupants by ‘hearing’ human-generated sounds like talking or typing while filtering out ambient noise. 
With dual technology, you can have the high-performance lighting environment that you want without sacrificing energy efficiency. In its dual technology lineup, Sensor Switch offers a series of occupancy sensors that offers the best value for your light control investment.
